    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>A green pigment originally composed of basic copper chloride (atacamite), developed in 1795 by the Brunswick brothers by placing copper filings in an ammonium chloride solution, then collecting the precipitate. By the 19th century, Brunswick green was prepared by mixing Prussian blue and chrome yellow, although this mixture is more commonly called "chrome green."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047822/MFA Conservation and Art Material Encyclopedia Online: CAMEO (2005-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一種原先以鹼式氯化銅（氯銅礦）製成的綠色顏料，由布倫瑞克（Brunswick）兄弟在西元1795年發明，在氯化銨溶液中加入銅屑，之後收集沉澱物而成。到了十九世紀，以混合普魯士藍和鉻黃製成布倫瑞克綠，不過此混合物較常被稱為「鉻綠 (顏料)」。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
